text: Analytical   pyrolysis   evidences   the   presence   of   granaticins   in   the   violet stains   of   a   Roman   tomb Marta   Diaz-Herraiz a,   Leonila   Laiz a,   Valme   Jurado a,   Ana   Z.   Miller a, Jose   Antonio   Gonzalez-Perez a,   Juan   Luis   Santos b,   Esteban   Alonso b, Cesareo   Saiz-Jimenez a,∗ a Instituto  de  Recursos  Naturales  y  Agrobiologia,  IRNAS-CSIC,  Avenida  Reina  Mercedes  10,  41012  Sevilla,  Spain b Escuela  Politecnica  Superior,  Universidad  de  Sevilla,  Virgen  de  Africa  7,  41011  Sevilla,  Spain Article  history: Received  10  August  2015 Received  in  revised  form 28  September  2015 Accepted  6  October  2015 Available  online  25  November  2015 Keywords: Granaticins Streptomyces Roman  tomb Mortar Pyrolysis High  performance  liquid  chromatography Colored  stains  in  cultural  heritage  sites  and  monuments  are  due to  chlorophylls,  carotenoid  pigments,  anthraquinones,  melanins, etc.  produced  by  bacteria,  fungi,  algae  and  lichens  [1–4].  Acti- nobacterial  growth  on  building  materials  produces  a  variety  of colorations  usually  related  with  the  excretion  of  secondary  metabo- lites,  including  antibiotics  and  pigments  [5].

Violet  staining  on  paintings  and  mortars  are  rare  in  cultural  her- itage  properties.  This  phenomenon  was  only  previously  reported  in two  Etruscan  tombs.  However,  no  data  on  the  bacterial  species  pro- ducing  the  pigments  and  their  chemical  structure  were  reported [6]. The  Circular  Mausoleum  tomb,  at  the  Roman  Necropolis  of Carmona,  Spain,  dates  back  from  the  1st  century  AD  and  is  char- acterized  by  the  abundant  presence  of  violet  stains  on  the  walls (Fig.  1).  Sampling  campaigns  allowed  us  to  isolate  and  charac- terize  two  Streptomyces  strains  involved  in  the  production  of  a diffusible  violet  pigment  on  the  tomb  walls,  which  originates  a noticeable  biodeterioration. The   walls   of   the   Circular   Mausoleum   tomb   (Roman   Necropolis   of  Carmona,   Spain)   exhibit   an   important number   of  violet   stains   of   unknown   origin.   Analytical   pyrolysis   detected   in   the   tomb   walls   granaticin A,   a   violet   pigment   with   an   isobenzochromanequinone   structure,   as   well   as   in   the  extracts   of   two   bac- terial   strains   isolated   from   the  walls.   The   bacterium   was   tentatively   identiﬁed   as  Streptomyces   sp.  High performance   liquid   chromatography   conﬁrmed   that   this   Streptomyces   synthesized   as  major   pigments dihydrogranaticin   A,   granaticin   A   and   granaticin   B. Contents  lists  available  at  ScienceDirect the  violet  pigments,  either  in  nature  or  in  the  laboratory,  together with  the  identiﬁcation  of  the  violet  pigment  by  analytical  pyrolysis and  the  conﬁrmation  of  the  pigments  synthesized  by  the  bacterium using  high  performance  liquid  chromatography–mass  spectrome- try  permitted  to  disclose  the  nature  of  the  violet  stains  and  related pigments. 2.1.  Sampling  of  violet  stains In  the  years  1997  and  2005  were  conducted  two   sampling campaigns  in  the  Circular  Mausoleum  tomb,  Roman  Necropolis of  Carmona,  Spain.  The  samplings  were  focused  on  the  isolation of  bacteria  producing  violet  stains.  The  violet  stains  were  gently scrapped  using  a  sterilized  scalpel,  and  placed  into  sterile  tubes.

The  samples  for  bacteria  isolation  were  processed  the  day  of sampling  and  inoculated  on  Petri  plates  containing  solid  tryptone soy  agar  (TSA)  medium  with  0.2%  glycerol.  Cultures  were  incu- bated  at  30 ◦C  for  several  weeks  and  the  species  producing  violet pigments  were  isolated.  The  bacterium  Streptomyces  vietnamensis DSM  41927,  reported  to  produce  violet  pigments  [7],  was  used  for comparative  studies. ©   2015   Elsevier   B.V.   All   rights   reserved. Fig.  1.  Violet  stains  in  the  Circular  Mausoleum,  Roman  Necropolis  of  Carmona,  Spain.  A:  Back  wall  of  the  tomb.  B:  Details  of  violet  stains  from  A.  C:  Violet  stains  in  the  right wall.   D:  Violet  stains  in  the  left  wall. 2.2.  16S  rDNA  identiﬁcation  of  isolates

Bacterial  isolates  producing  violet  pigments  were  identiﬁed  by direct  PCR  from  colonies.  DNA  was  extracted  by  dispersing  a  bac- (cid:2)L  of  10  mM  TE  buffer,  and  freeze–thawing  at terial  colony  in  100  −80 ◦C  and  65 ◦C,  respectively.  PCR  was  performed  with  primers 616F  and  1510R  [8].  Ampliﬁcation  consisted  of  denaturing  step  of 2  min   at  94 ◦C,  followed  by  35  cycles  of  denaturing  at  94 ◦C  for  20  s, annealing  at  55 ◦C  for  45  s,  and  elongation  at  72 ◦C  for  2  min,  follow- ing  a  terminal  step  of  10  min   at  72 ◦C.  The  PCR  products  were  run  on a  1%  (w/v)  agarose  gels  and  puriﬁed  using  the  JetQuick  PCR  Puriﬁ- cation  Spin  Kit  (Genomed,  Löhne,  Germany).  DNA  sequencing  of the  PCR  products  was  carried  out  by  Macrogen  Europe  Sequencing Services  (Amsterdam,  The  Netherlands).  Sequences  were  phyloge- netically  classiﬁed  and  their  nearest  relative  identiﬁed  using  the BLASTN  algorithm.  The  isolates  were  identiﬁed  using  the  EzTaxon server  (http://www.ezbiocloud.net/eztaxon)  [9]  on  the  basis  of  16S rRNA  sequence  data. 2.3.  Pigment  extraction  and  analysis

Liquid  medium  used  for  pigment  production  was  described by  Hopwood  et  al.  [10].  The  pigments  were  extracted  with  ethyl acetate  and  analyzed  by  thin  layer  chromatography  (TLC)  on  silica gel  plates  (HPTLC  silica  gel  60  Merck,  Damstadt,  Germany),  using the  solvents  chloroform/acetic  acid,  4:1.  All  reagents  and  solvents used  were  of  analytical  grade. The  chemical  nature  of  the  pigments  was  investigated  by analytical  pyrolysis  and  liquid  chromatography–mass  spectrome- try  (HPLC–MS).  For  analytical  pyrolysis  the  materials  containing pigments  i.e.,  small  pieces  of  violet  stained  mortar  were deposited  on  small  crucible  capsules  while  liquid  extracts  were directly  deposited  on  a  stainless  steel  pyrolysis  wire  (Eco-cup and  Ecos-stick;  Frontier  Labs.,  Fukushima,  Japan).  Pyrolysis- gas  chromatography/mass  spectrometry  was  performed  using  a double-shot  pyrolyzer  (Frontier  Labs.  model  2020i)  attached  to a  GC/MS  system  Agilent  6890N,  as  described  by  González-Pérez M.   Diaz-Herraiz  et  al.  /  Journal  of  Analytical  and  Applied  Pyrolysis  117  (2016)  357–362

et  al.  [11].  Brieﬂy,  the  samples  were  introduced  into  a  preheated micro-furnace  set  at  temperatures  of  100–250 ◦C  for  thermal  des- orption  and/or  at  350–500 ◦C  for  pyrolysis.  The  analytical  protocol was  set  at  150 ◦C  for  thermal  desorption  and  350 ◦C  for  pyroly- sis,  which  provided  the  best  results.  The  compounds  evolved  were then  directly  injected  into  the  GC/MS  for  analysis.  The  gas  chro- matograph  was   equipped  with  a  HP-5ms-UI  capillary  column.  The detector  consisted  of  an  Agilent  5973  mass  selective  detector,  and mass  spectra  were  acquired  at  70  eV  ionizing  energy.  Compound assignments  were  achieved  by  single-ion  monitoring  (SIM)  and  by comparison  with  mass  spectra  [12].

HPLC–MS  analyses  were  performed  as  described  by  Martín  et  al. [13].  Brieﬂy,  an  Agilent  1200  series  HPLC  equipped  with  a  Zorbax (cid:2)m) Eclipse  XDB-C18  Rapid  Resolution  HT  (4.6  column  was   used.  Elution  was  carried  out  with  acetonitrile  (con- taining  formic  acid  0.1%,  v/v)  (solvent  A)  and  aqueous  10  mM ammonium  formate  solution  (containing  formic  acid  0.1%,  v/v) (solvent  B),  at  a  ﬂow  rate  of  0.6  mL/min  with  the  column  ther- mostated  at  25 ◦C.  The  elution  programme  used  was:  0–7.5  min: linear  gradient  from  10%  to  35%  of  solvent  A,  7.5–14.5  min:  iso- cratic  35%  solvent  A,  14.5–14.6  min:  linear  gradient  from  35%  to 100%  of  solvent  A,  14.6–18.5  min:  isocratic  100%  solvent  A.  Mass spectrometry  analyses  were  performed  on  an  Agilent  6410  QqQ instrument  equipped  with  an  electrospray  ionization  source.  Ion- ization  of  analytes  was  carried  out  using  the  following  settings:  MS capillary  voltage:  3000  V,  drying-gas  ﬂow  rate:  9  L/min,  drying-gas temperature:  350 ◦C  and  nebulizer  pressure:  40  psi.

Each  extract  was   measured  using  scan  and  product  ion  modes. Firstly,  scan  mode  was  applied  to  the  determination  of  the  reten- tion  time  of  each  of  the  studied  compounds.  Scan  was  carried  out using  positive  polarity  and  applying  a  voltage  to  the  exit  end  of  the capillary  (fragmentor)  of  50  V.  Mass  spectra  were  registered  from m/z   80  to  950. Product  ion  mode  was   carried  out,  using  positive  polarity,  for  the monitorization  of  the  ions  of  m/z   445,  447  and  559,  corresponding to  ions  [M  +  1]+  of  granaticin  A,  dihydrogranaticin  and  granaticin B,  respectively.  The  applied  fragmentor  was   50  V  and  the  voltage applied  to  the  ions  in  the  collision  cell  (collision  energy)  was  12  V. MS/MS   spectra  from  m/z  50  to  570  were  obtained  using  a  scan  time of  300  ms. 3.  Results  and  discussion 3.1.  Bacterial  isolation Two  bacteria  (strains  MC48  and  MC05)  producing  a  diffusible violet  pigment  under  laboratory  conditions  were  isolated  from  the violet  stains  in  samplings  conducted  in  the  years  1997  and  2005, respectively.  The  two  bacteria  produced  the  same  pigments.

Using  the  EzTaxon  database  [9],  MC48  and  MC05  strains  showed 99.86%  similarity  with  Streptomyces  pluricolorescens,  S.  rubiginoso- helvolus  and  S.  globisporus,   therefore  we  labeled  our  strains  as Streptomyces  sp. 3.2.  Pigment  production Two  Streptomyces  strains  isolated  from  the  violet  stains  of  the Circular  Mausoleum  were  able  to  synthesize  violet  compounds  in Fig.  2.  Thin  layer  chromatography  of  violet  extracts.  A:  Streptomyces  vietnamensis.  B:  Streptomyces  strain  MC05. M.  Diaz-Herraiz  et  al.  /  Journal  of  Analytical  and  Applied  Pyrolysis  117  (2016)  357–362  a  medium  used  for  pigment  production  [10].  The  pigment,  violet in  alkaline  media,  turned  out  red  in  acid  media  which  denotes  a quinone  structure. Few  Streptomyces  species  have  been  reported  to  produce  vio- let  or  blue  pigments.  We   compared  the  two  isolated  strains  with S.  vietnamensis  type  strain  [7],  which  was  selected  as  control  and representative  bacteria  for  violet  pigment  production. Thin  layer  chromatography  (TLC)  of  the  pigments  extracted  from S.  vietnamensis  and  strain  MC05  showed  similar  Rf for  three  main pigments  (Fig.  2).  MC48  showed  identical  TLC  pattern.  Chromato- graphic  data  suggested  that  the  pigments  synthesized  by  strain MC05  could  be  related  to  the  granaticins  produced  by  S.  vietna- mensis  [14].

The  chemical  nature  of  the  violet  pigments  from  Streptomyces MC05  strain  and  S.  vietnamensis  was   also  disclosed  by  analyti- cal  pyrolysis.  For  this  approach,  the  bacterial  culture  extracts  and pieces  of  the  tomb  mortars  were  subjected  to  several  thermal  des- orptions  (from  100  to  250 ◦C)  and  pyrolysis  conditions  (from  350◦C to  500 ◦C).  The  most  suitable  analytical  protocol  for  the  samples was  a  double  shot  consisting  on  a  ﬁrst  thermal  desorption  stage  at 150 ◦C,  releasing  lipids  and  other  volatile  compounds,  followed  by  a Fig.  3.  Analytical  pyrolysis  of  violet  pigments.  A:  Total  ion  chromatogram  and  mass  ion  chromatogram  (window)  of  S.  vietnamensis  culture  extract.  B:  Total  ion  chromatogram and   mass  ion  chromatogram  (window)  of  a  small  piece  of  violet-colored  mortar. thermal  desorption/mild  pyrolysis  at  350 ◦C  allowing  the  volatiliza- tion  of  high  molecular  weight  products.

Analytical  pyrolysis  of  the  violet  extract  produced  by  S.  viet- namensis  (Fig.  3A)  showed  a  conspicuous  peak  at  the  end  of  the chromatogram  (30.6  min),  both  under  thermal  desorption  at  150 ◦C and  mild  pyrolysis  conditions  at  350 ◦C,  with  a  mass  spectrum  char- −H+ ion  at  m/z   443, acterized  by  the  molecular  ion  at  m/z   444  and  characteristic  of  granaticin  A  (Fig.  3A).  The  same  pigment  and  mass spectrum  was  obtained  for  Streptomyces  MC05  strain  (data  not shown).  The  peak  corresponding  to  granaticin  A  was  also  obtained from  the  direct  analysis  of  a  small  piece  of  violet-colored  mortar from  the  tomb  (Fig.  3B). Analytical  pyrolysis  conﬁrmed  the  presence  of  granaticin  A  in the  culture  extracts  of  the  two  strains  of  Streptomyces  isolated  from the  tomb,  in  the  extract  of  S.  vietnamensis,  and  in  the  violet-stained mortar  collected  from  the  walls.  Thus,  analytical  pyrolysis  revealed to  be  a  useful  tool  for  the  direct  detection  of  granaticin  A  in  organic and  inorganic  matrices.  The  characteristic  ions  for  the  peak  found –  under  our  experimental  conditions  –  at  the  end  of  the  chro- matogram  (Fig.  3)  are  of  diagnostic  value  for  the  direct  conﬁrmation and  molecular  characterization  of  granaticin  A.

HPLC–MS  of  the  extracts  from  S.  vietnamensis  (Fig.  4A)  and  from strain  MC05  of  Streptomyces  (Fig.  4B)  conﬁrmed  the  production  of dihydrogranaticin  A,  granaticin  A  and  granaticin  B,  although  with different  relative  abundances  for  each  pigment.  Mass  spectra  of  the three  pigments  are  shown  in  Fig.  4C–D.  Granaticin  A  and  B  exhibited antibacterial  activity  against  Gram-positive  bacteria  and  inhibitory activity  against  several  cancer  cell  lines  [14].  The  production  of dihydrogranaticin  A  by  S.  vietnamensis  was  not  previously  reported by  Deng  et  al.  [14]. M.   Diaz-Herraiz  et  al.  /  Journal  of  Analytical  and  Applied  Pyrolysis  117  (2016)  357–362 To  conclude,  the  origin  of  the  violet  stains,  biodeteriorating  a Roman  tomb  from  the  ﬁrst  century  AD,  was  the  excretion  of  gra- naticins,  soluble  pigments  with  aromatic  polyketide  structure,  by Streptomyces  strains,  which  were  active  in  the  tomb,  as  they  were isolated  in  different  periods  of  time.  (Fig.  5).

The  major  violet  pigment,  granaticin  A,  is  soluble  in  alka- line  water  but  the  solubility  of  the  pigment  decreased  with  pH value.  The  pH  of  carbonated  lime  mortars  is  near  9,  which  per- mitted  the  solubilization  of  pigments  in  aqueous  medium.  It  can  be assumed  that  in  the  Circular  Mausoleum  tomb  and  during  grow- ing  periods  the  Streptomyces  synthesizes  the  violet  pigments  which diffuse  onto  the  mortar.  In  raining  and/or  wetting  (water  conden- sation)  periods,  the  pigments  were  solubilized  by  alkaline  water and  diffused  from  the  starting  position  to  the  surrounding  mortar, enlarging  the  pigmented  area  as  denoted  by  an  increasing  intensity on  the  stain  edges  and  a  lower  intensity  in  the  stain  centre,  as  can be  observed  in  Fig.  1D.

In  cultural  heritage  research  we   rarely  have  the  opportunity to  isolate  a  microorganism  which  reproduces  in  the  laboratory the  synthesis  of  pigments  causing  the  deterioration  phenom- ena,  as  shown  here.  Similar  violet  stains  were  also  present  on the  mural  paintings  from  the  Tomb  of  the  Chase  and  Fishing and  Tomb  of  the  Bulls,  Tarquinia,  Italy.  These  Etruscan  tombs were  sampled  in  July  2009,  but  no  pigment-producing  bacteria could  be  isolated  at  that  time,  probably  due  to  a  recent  clean- ing  and  restoration  intervention.  Sampling  on  the  violet-colored walls  was   not  allowed  by  the  Italian  cultural  authorities,  there- fore,  the  nature  of  the  violet  stains  in  Etruscan  tombs  still  remain unknown. C:  Mass  spectra  of peak   1:  Dihydrogranaticin  A  (Rt 9.2  min),  D:  Mass  spectra  of  peak  2:  Granaticin  A  (Rt 9.6  min),  E:  Mass  spectra  of  peak  3:  Granaticin  B  (Rt 23.9  min).
